versal deep human needs to care for the vulnerable – the sick, children and the elderly – and to maintain inter-generational solidarity. The authors argue that the financialisation of social relations undermines the foundations of civilisation and opens up a marketised barbarism. Civic catastrophes of violent conflict and authoritarian liberalism are here illustrated as aspects of the 'rough beast' that slouches in when things are falling apart and people become prey to new forms of domination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEconomic assistance, DomesticxIreland. 0aEconomic assistance, DomesticzIreland. 0aEconomicsxIreland. 0aEconomicszIreland. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ireland.2bisacsh  aAthenians.  aIrish development.  aIrish mythic story.  aIrish republic.  aPlato's Republic.  aThe Second Coming.  aW. B. Yeats.  aaesthetic idea.  acollective household.  adomestic economies.  afairness and justice.  aghost estates.  ahaunted houses.  amoral economies.  aneoliberal revolution.  apolitical economies.  apost-Celtic Tiger Ireland.  asymbolic order.  atax free zones.  atyranny.1 aKeohane, Kieran, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuhling, Carmen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKuhling, Carmen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packagez978311128357940uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610219540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526102195423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526102195/original  a978-3-11-128357-9  Manchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packageb2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles